docs.abstract: The company continues to lean on customers’ appetite for apps and services, as demand for its devices weakens.
docs.snippet: The company continues to lean on customers’ appetite for apps and services, as demand for its devices weakens.
docs.lead_paragraph: Difficulties have been piling up for Apple. In recent months, it has been sued by the Justice Department, fined by European regulators and challenged by the resurgence of a Chinese smartphone competitor.

headline.main: Apple Reports Decline in Sales and Profit Amid iPhone Struggles in China
headline.print_headline: Apple Reports 4 Percent Fall In Its Revenue

docs.abstract: A class-action lawsuit about audio issues in iPhone 7 and 7 Plus phones has led to a $35 million settlement, though the company denies the phones were faulty.
docs.snippet: A class-action lawsuit about audio issues in iPhone 7 and 7 Plus phones has led to a $35 million settlement, though the company denies the phones were faulty.
docs.lead_paragraph: Some Apple customers who owned an iPhone 7 or 7 Plus and experienced audio issues may be entitled to up to $349 as part of a proposed $35 million settlement on a class-action lawsuit.

headline.main: Some iPhone Customers Could Get Up to $349 in an Apple Settlement

docs.abstract: Apple plans to announce that it will bring generative A.I. to iPhones after the company’s most significant reorganization in a decade.
docs.snippet: Apple plans to announce that it will bring generative A.I. to iPhones after the company’s most significant reorganization in a decade.
docs.lead_paragraph: Apple’s top software executives decided early last year that Siri, the company’s virtual assistant, needed a brain transplant.

headline.main: Apple Will Revamp Siri to Catch Up to Its Chatbot Competitors
headline.print_headline: Hey Siri, Get Ready for Your A.I. Upgrade

docs.abstract: Berkshire Hathaway shareholders will gather in Omaha for the conglomerate’s annual meeting on Saturday, with questions about the company’s future.
docs.snippet: Berkshire Hathaway shareholders will gather in Omaha for the conglomerate’s annual meeting on Saturday, with questions about the company’s future.
docs.lead_paragraph: Tens of thousands of investors are flocking to Omaha this weekend, which can mean only one thing: It’s time for Berkshire Hathaway’s annual shareholder meeting, dubbed the “Woodstock for capitalists.”

headline.main: What Will Warren Buffett Bet on Next?
headline.print_headline: Investors Flock to Hear What Buffett Will Bet on Next

byline.original: By Andrew Ross Sorkin, Ravi Mattu, Bernhard Warner, Sarah Kessler, Michael J. de la Merced, Lauren Hirsch and Ephrat Livni

docs.abstract: An ad meant to show how the updated device can do many things has become a metaphor for a community’s fears of the technology industry.
docs.snippet: An ad meant to show how the updated device can do many things has become a metaphor for a community’s fears of the technology industry.
docs.lead_paragraph: The trumpet is the first thing to be squished. Then the industrial compressor flattens a row of paint cans, buckles a piano and levels what appears to be a marble bust. In a final act of destruction, it pops the eyes out of a ball-shaped yellow emoji.

headline.main: Apple’s New iPad Ad Leaves Its Creative Audience Feeling … Flat
headline.print_headline: Apple Spot Has Creators  Feeling Flat

docs.abstract: “Did you ever think we would have a literal Avenger fighting back against the relentless march of A.I.? Because that’s sort of what this story is about.”
docs.snippet: “Did you ever think we would have a literal Avenger fighting back against the relentless march of A.I.? Because that’s sort of what this story is about.”
docs.lead_paragraph: This week, more drama at OpenAI: The company wanted Scarlett Johansson to be a voice of GPT-4o, she said no … but something got lost in translation. Then we talk with Noland Arbaugh, the first person to get Elon Musk’s Neuralink device implanted in his brain, about how his brain-computer interface has changed his life. And finally, the Times’s Karen Weise reports back from Microsoft’s developer conference, where the big buzz was that the company’s new line of A.I. PCs will record every single thing you do on the device.

headline.main: ScarJo vs. ChatGPT, Neuralink’s First Patient Opens Up, and Microsoft’s A.I. PCs

docs.abstract: As the Justice Department’s case against Google nears an end, the federal government has more suits in the pipeline trying to rein in Big Tech.
docs.snippet: As the Justice Department’s case against Google nears an end, the federal government has more suits in the pipeline trying to rein in Big Tech.
docs.lead_paragraph: The U.S. government’s landmark antitrust trial against Google’s search business is nearing its conclusion. But the parade of major federal cases challenging Big Tech’s power is just getting going.

headline.main: U.S. Antitrust Case Against Google Is Just the Start
headline.print_headline: A Battle Royal of Antitrust Cases Between U.S. Government and Big Tech

byline.original: By Cecilia Kang and David McCabe

docs.abstract: A trial had been set to hear evidence that organizers of a 2021 Travis Scott concert knew the crowd was too large and ignored pleas to stop it as 10 people were crushed.
docs.snippet: A trial had been set to hear evidence that organizers of a 2021 Travis Scott concert knew the crowd was too large and ignored pleas to stop it as 10 people were crushed.
docs.lead_paragraph: A lawyer for Live Nation, the concert company, said in court on Wednesday that settlements had been reached in all but one of the lawsuits over the deaths of 10 people who were fatally crushed during a performance by Travis Scott at the 2021 Astroworld festival in Houston.

headline.main: ‘Someone’s Going to End Up Dead’: Settlements Over Fatal Astroworld Concert

docs.abstract: People in the creative world widely panned a commercial showing a giant hydraulic press squishing objects ranging from paint cans to a piano.
docs.snippet: People in the creative world widely panned a commercial showing a giant hydraulic press squishing objects ranging from paint cans to a piano.
docs.lead_paragraph: Apple doesn’t make mistakes often and seldom apologizes, but on Thursday, its head of advertising said the company had erred in making a new iPad commercial that showed an industrial compressor flattening tools for art, music and creativity.

headline.main: Apple Says Destructive iPad Ad ‘Missed the Mark’
